Hashmi Gold-Catalyzed One-Pot A3-Coupling/1,5-Hydrogen  Shift/Schmittel-Type Cyclization: From Aldehydes, Amines and  Alkynes to the Synthesis of Benzo[b]fluorenes  Danilo M. Lustosa[a], Deborah Hartmann[a], Matthias Rudolph[a], Frank Rominger[a], A. Stephen K.  Hashmi*[a,b]

Abstract:  A  step-economic  gold-catalyzed  one-pot  synthesis  of  benzo[b]fluorenes, from aldehydes, alkynes and amines, proceeding  via  an  A3-coupling/1,5-hydrogen  shift/Schmittel-type  cyclization  is  described. The formation of the allene intermediate is not dependent  on  a  previous  installation  of  reaction  triggers,  and  upon  cyclization  delivered  benzo[b]fluorenes.  With  this  method,  just  by  an  easy  modification  of  the  starting  materials,  in  a  modular  way  nineteen  benzo[b]fluorenes,  bearing  different  substituents    Ar1,  Ar2  and  Ar3,  were prepared. Overall, three new carbon-carbon bonds are formed  in one-pot..

Benzo[b]fluorenes  are  polycyclic  non-alternant  aromatic  hydrocarbons with potential for applications in material science.[1]  They  also  share  their  central  core  with  different  natural  metabolites,  such  as  Kinobscurinone,[2]  Stealthin  C  [2-3]  and  the  antibiotic  family  of  the  Kinamycins.[2-4]  Despite  their  potential,  compared to other polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs) and  non-alternant PAHs, the use of benzo[b]fluorenes, especially as  organic material, is still underexplored.[1,5] This can be rationalized  by  the  lack  of  efficient  synthetic  methods  for  the  synthesis  of  diversely substituted representatives of this class of compounds.  Their  synthesis  is  normally  achieved  either  by  direct  thermal  cyclizations of 1,6-dienes[6] or by a Schmittel-type cyclization[7]. In  1996, Schmittel (Scheme 1.a) reported the cyclization of I in the  presence  of  a  hydrogen  donor  to  furnish  II.[6a-c]  To  avoid  the  preparation of the allene precursors, the method evolved to use  an  in  situ  generation  of  the  allene  and  a  direct  trapping  by  a  Schmittel  reaction  (Scheme  1b  –  d).  Select  examples  of  this  strategy in the field of gold catalyzed reactions are the first report  in 2012 by Shi, who used a [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangment of a  propargylvinylether to furnished the allene (Scheme 1.b)[7a] and,

later, Liu’s (2012; Scheme 1.c)[7b] and Hashmi’s (2015; Scheme  1.d)[7c]  works,  in  which  they  have  both  explored  carboxyl  migrations  to  induce  a  similar  transformation.  Despite  the  elegancy of these approaches, the in-situ generated allenes are  all formed by previously installed reaction triggers to first undergo  a  [3,3]  sigmatropic  rearrangement,  causing  additional  synthetic  steps. Recently we reported a one-pot atom- and step-economic  method  for  the  synthesis  of  benzo[b]fluorenes  from  aldehydes,  alkynes and amines, proceeding via an A3-coupling/formal [4+2]  thermal cycloaddition, leading to two different benzo[b]fluorenes  regioisomers  as  products  (Scheme  1.e).[6i]  On  the  other  hand,  from  inspired  by  gold-catalyzed  1,5-hydrogen  migrations  propagylamines,[8]  we  also  have  reported  that  allenes  can  be  synthesized  from  aldehydes,  alkynes  and  morpholine,  through  propagylamine  intermediates.[9]    In  this  context,  aiming  to  integrate  our  allene  synthesis  into  a  cascade  reaction,  we  envisioned that the allene VI could be formed in situ, with no need  for  from  propargylamine  V    (Scheme  1f).  A  subsequent  trapping  of  this  allene VI in a Schmittel-type cyclization would then be feasible.  Overall, a gold-catalyzed one-pot synthesis of benzo[b]fluorenes  by  using  easily  accessible  and  available  starting  materials  (morpholine,  aldehyde  and  alkyne)  was  in  our  focus. and  alkyne)  was  in  our  focus.  This  new  process  would  not  only  avoid  the  pre-installation  of  reaction  triggers,  but  also  present  an  alternative  method  which  circumvents  regioselectivity  problems  -  a  drawback  of  our  previous  study.6  Additionally,  by  avoiding  the  installation  of  functional groups, this method can lead to the one-pot formation  of three new carbon-carbon bonds and cuts down the number of  synthetic  steps  usually  required  to  access  benzo[b]fluorenes.  Ultimately,  by  applying  our  allene  synthesis  method  to  this  reaction,[9]  we  also  hope  to  not  only  to  demonstrate  that  this  method  is  interesting  for  the  synthesis  of  benzo[b]fluorenes  themselves  but  also  to  illustrate  how  easily  allenes  can  be  accessed as intermediates in cascade reactions.

The  first  step  of  our  proposed  transformation,  the  A3-coupling  reaction for the formation of 4a, was previously reported by our  group.[6i]  We  used  the  best  solvents  reported  to  successfully  promote  this  transformation  (Table  1,  entries  1-3)  and  chose  IPrAuNTf2 as catalyst to start optimizing the direct cyclization of  4a  to  6a.  Both  toluene  and  tBuOH  led  to  the  formation  of  benzo[b]fluorene 6a in low yield (entries 1 - 2), whereas DCE led  to a slight improvement, reaching up to 35% (entry 3 and 5). TFE  was also evaluated (entry 4), but it was not superior. No complete  conversion of 4a could be observed, which indicates deactivation  of  the  catalyst  during  the  reaction.  To  overcome  this,  additives  were  tested.  When  HNTf2  was  used,  an  unselective  decomposition  of  the  starting  material  was  detected  (entry  6),  whereas  use  of  acidic  amberlyst-15  improved  the  yield  to  45%  (entry 7). In  order  to  combine  the  two  steps  in  a  single  pot,  first,  the  A3- coupling  reaction  conditions  previously  reported  by  us,[6i]  were  applied  to  aldehyde  1a,  morpholine  and  alkyne  2a  dissolved  in  tBuOH along with IPrAuNTf2 at 70 °C. After full conversion, tBuOH  was removed and DCE was added as solvent for the second step  along with amberlyst-15 H+ (15 mg). After another 48 h, at 50 °C,  a yield of 26% of benzo[b]fluorene 6a was obtained (Table 2, entry  1).  Next,  the  whole  transformation  was  performed  in  tBuOH, by  first heating the reaction at 70 °C, overnight. After amberlyst-15  H+ was added and the reaction was heated for additional 48 h, at  50  °C.  To  our  delight,  benzo[b]fluorene  6a  was  obtained  in  a  satisfactory  yield  of  52%  over  three  steps  (Table  2,  entry  3).  If  considered  the  A3-coupling,  the  allene  synthesis  and  the  Schmittel-cyclization  as  three  different  separated  steps,  an  average yield of 80% per step can be considered. An attempt to  perform  the  whole  transformation  in  DCE  led  to  a  decrease  in  yield to 17% (Table 2, entry 3). The addition of amberlyst at the  very  beginning  of  the  reaction  also  reduced  the  yield  (Table  2  entry  4).  It  is  important  to  highlight  that  for  an  unbiased  determination  of  the  structures  of  benzo[b]fluorene  6a,  X-ray  crystallography analysis was performed (Figure 1)[10]

to  reports  on  1,5-migration  of  hydrogen  on  In  analogy  propagylamines[8-9,11]  and  the  reports  on  the  in-situ  allene  trappings  to  benzo[b]fluorenes,[7a-c]  we  propose  the  reaction  mechanism to be initiated by an A3-coupling reaction to afford the  propargylamine 4, which then can undergo a 1,5-hydride shift to  generate A, and after elimination the allene 5. Once formed, the  allene  directly  engages  in  an  Au-catalyzed  Schmittel-type  cyclization  by  first  coordinating  to  gold[12]  (as  depicted  by  intermediate B). This intermediate then cyclizes into the cationic  species  C,  which  after  an  electrophilic  aromatic  substitution,  deprotonation  and  a  protodeauration[13]  furnishes  the  desired  benzo[b]fluorene 6 (Scheme 2).  2)  amberlyst  (15  mg) 50  °C, 48  h 1)  IPrAuNTf2 t-BuOH 70  °C, over  night Scheme 2. Proposed mechanistic cycle for the Au-catalyzed synthesis of  benzo[b]fluorenes via an one-pot A3-coupling/1,5-hydride shift/Schmittel-type  cyclization.

Our  attempts  to  isolate  or  detect  intermediate  5  failed,  which  indicates  that  its  conversion  via  a  Schmittel-type  cyclization  is  faster  than  the  allene  formation.  As  an  alternative,  we  used  an  alkyl  alkyne  2t  (Scheme  3),  which  under  the  standard  reaction  conditions with 1a indeed led to the formation of an allene, 5t, as  detected  via  1H  NMR.  Thus,  it  is  highly  likely  that  this  is  an  intermediate in the catalytic cycle with aromatic alkynes as well.   Scheme 3. Synthesis of allene 5t  Overall,  we  have  described  an  alternative  step-economic  Au- catalyzed  one-pot  synthesis  of  benzo[b]fluorenes  from  easily  accessible  starting  materials  (terminal  alkynes,  morpholine  and  benzaldehyde  derivatives).  The  reaction  is  believed  to  proceed  via  a  sequence  of  A3-Coupling/1,5-H-shift/Schmittel-type  cyclization reaction, which forms three new carbon-carbon bonds.  In  contrast  to  existing  methods,  in  this  approach,  the  allene  intermediate is generated with no need for previous installation of  reaction triggers. Finally, varying the starting materials, nineteen  benzo[b]fluorenes could be prepared in a modular way, bearing  different substitution pattern (at Ar1, Ar2 and Ar3).
